#. type: Content of: <guide><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:6
#, no-wrap
msgid "The Openbox Configuration HOWTO"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><abstract>
#: en/openbox.xml:16
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This guide shows you how to install the Openbox window manager, and references\n"
"many potential programs to be used in conjunction with an Openbox session.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:28
#, no-wrap
msgid "Introduction"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:31
#, no-wrap
msgid "What is Openbox?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:35
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"So, you've installed <uri link=\"/doc/en/xorg-config.xml\">The X Server</uri> and\n"
"realised that TWM just isn't going to cut it for your needs. You may have also\n"
"had some experience with big desktop environments like <uri\n"
"link=\"/proj/en/desktop/kde/kde4-guide.xml\">KDE</uri>, <uri\n"
"link=\"/doc/en/gnome-config.xml\">GNOME</uri>, and <uri\n"
"link=\"/doc/en/xfce-config.xml\">Xfce</uri>. One component of those larger desktop\n"
"suites is called the window manager (or WM for short). A window manager is\n"
"responsible for the appearance and placement of the containers (or \"windows\")\n"
"inside which programs run. Openbox is a minimalistic, no-frills-attached window\n"
"manager.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:50
#, no-wrap
msgid "Why should I use it?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:54
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Openbox, unlike the larger desktop environments, depends on very few libraries.\n"
"For that reason, it can provide a lightweight graphic environment that runs\n"
"very quickly, even on older hardware. Whether your hardware is old or new,\n"
"Openbox also provides a highly customisable and unobtrusive working\n"
"environment. That means that if you don't want or need a panel, taskbar, clock,\n"
"or any other program, those choices are yours to make!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:67
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installation and configuration"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:69
#, no-wrap
msgid "Initial installation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:73
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"After you have emerged and configured <c>xorg-server</c>, installing Openbox can\n"
"be done in one simple command:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:77
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing Openbox"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:78
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>emerge -av openbox</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:82
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Just like with other window managers and desktop environments, you will need to\n"
"tell the X Server to load Openbox automatically, by adding it to your\n"
"<path>~/.xinitrc</path>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:87
#, no-wrap
msgid "Adding Openbox to your .xinitrc"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:88
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>echo \"exec openbox-session\" >> ~/.xinitrc</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:92
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This will automatically start your Openbox session when you type <c>startx</c>\n"
"at the terminal.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><impo>
#: en/openbox.xml:97
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"As each user has his or her own <path>.xinitrc</path>, you need to make sure to\n"
"issue that command as <e>your user</e>, not as root.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><note>
#: en/openbox.xml:102
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you experience problems with automounting, or if you use dbus and ConsoleKit,\n"
"you may want to put <c>exec ck-launch-session dbus-launch --sh-syntax\n"
"--exit-with-session openbox-session</c> in your <path>.xinitrc</path> instead of\n"
"the default mentioned above.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><note>
#: en/openbox.xml:109
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You can also replace the KDE, GNOME, or Xfce default window manager with\n"
"Openbox by following the <uri link=\"#inside-desktop-env\">Openbox inside desktop\n"
"environments</uri> directions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:115
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now that you have emerged Openbox and added it to your <path>.xinitrc</path>,\n"
"go ahead and issue the <c>startx</c> command to see Openbox in action. As you\n"
"can see, the desktop is simply a cluttered mess! In following with the Openbox\n"
"philosophy, what you will see is a barebones environment from which you can\n"
"build your desktop completely to your liking.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:123
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Since you're looking at nothing more than a black screen, you may be wondering\n"
"where the menu is. If you click your right mouse button, you will notice that a\n"
"menu pops up in the location of your cursor. This menu is nothing more than an\n"
"example to illustrate the style of an Openbox menu. Since it <e>is</e> just an\n"
"example, none of the items in the menu will work unless you have actually\n"
"emerged those programs. In the next section, you will see how to create your\n"
"own menu that contains links to <e>your</e> programs.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><impo>
#: en/openbox.xml:133
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you click to view the menu and notice that there is nothing legible, you need\n"
"to install some fonts. Two common choices are <c>media-fonts/corefonts</c> and\n"
"<c>media-fonts/ttf-bitstream-vera</c>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:141
#, no-wrap
msgid "Menu configuration"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:145
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Since the default Openbox menu is essentially useless to you for the reasons\n"
"mentioned above, it's time that we create one that will work. Everything in the\n"
"Openbox menu is written in the appropriately named <path>menu.xml</path> file,\n"
"which can be in the user-specific location of\n"
"<path>~/.config/openbox/menu.xml</path>, or in the system-wide location of\n"
"<path>/etc/xdg/openbox/menu.xml</path>. By default, the only\n"
"<path>menu.xml</path> file that is created is the system-wide one which applies\n"
"to all users on the system.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:156
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"An easy way to get a basic menu file which you can modify is to use MenuMaker,\n"
"which will generate a <path>menu.xml</path> file based on the programs which\n"
"you currently have installed on your system. To do so, you must firstly emerge\n"
"it:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:162
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing MenuMaker"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:163
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>emerge menumaker</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:167
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Once it is installed, make sure to logout of root, and back into your user\n"
"account.  You then instruct MenuMaker to create a menu specifically using the\n"
"Openbox XML syntax:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:172
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using MenuMaker to generate a basic Openbox menu.xml"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:173
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>mmaker -v OpenBox3</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:177
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The generated menu will be located at\n"
"<path>~/.config/openbox/menu.xml</path>. You can then choose to leave it as \n"
"your user-specific <path>menu.xml</path>, or to additionally copy it to the \n"
"system-wide menu configuration as well:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:183
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overwriting the default system-wide menu.xml files"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:184
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>cp .config/openbox/menu.xml /etc/xdg/openbox/menu.xml</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><impo>
#: en/openbox.xml:188
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"It is a good idea to use MenuMaker to generate a default menu, as it will have\n"
"the Openbox root-menu items. These items include a virtual desktop switcher,\n"
"and the commands to restart and exit your Openbox session.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:194
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"When you open up the <path>menu.xml</path> file in your favourite editor (nano,\n"
"for example), you will notice that the XML tags used are very human-readable\n"
"and easily understandable. You may choose to modify the default file to fit\n"
"your needs, or you may want to write it from scratch (don't worry, it's really\n"
"not that difficult). The basic syntax for the menu XML is as follows:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:201 en/openbox.xml:220 en/openbox.xml:285
#, no-wrap
msgid "Editing the menu.xml file"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:202
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"&lt;?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?&gt;\n"
"&lt;openbox_menu&gt;\n"
"&lt;separator label=\"NAME_OF_SEPARATOR\" /&gt;\n"
"&lt;menu id=\"IDENTIFIER\" label=\"NAME_OF_MENU\"&gt;\n"
"  &lt;item label=\"NAME_OF_PROGRAM\"&gt;\n"
"    &lt;action name=\"execute\"&gt;&lt;execute&gt;/LOCATION/OF/BINARY&lt;/execute&gt;&lt;/action&gt;\n"
"  &lt;/item&gt;\n"
"&lt;/menu&gt;\n"
"&lt;/openbox_menu&gt;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:214
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The above example will work for any applications that launch with standard \n"
"options in their own windows, but what if you need to append options to \n"
"the program at launch time?  That is no problem either, but the syntax of \n"
"the menu item is slightly different.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:221
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"&lt;?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?&gt;\n"
"&lt;openbox_menu&gt;\n"
"&lt;separator label=\"NAME_OF_SEPARATOR\" /&gt;\n"
"&lt;menu id=\"IDENTIFIER\" label=\"NAME_OF_MENU\"&gt;\n"
"  &lt;item label=\"NAME_OF_PROGRAM\"&gt;\n"
"    &lt;action name=\"execute\"&gt;&lt;command&gt;/LOCATION/OF/BINARY --OPTION1 --OPTION2&lt;/command&gt;&lt;/action&gt;\n"
"  &lt;/item&gt;\n"
"&lt;/menu&gt;\n"
"&lt;/openbox_menu&gt;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:233
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Simply replace anything in CAPS in the above two examples with your information.\n"
"Alternatively, you can <c>emerge obmenu</c>, which is a graphical interface \n"
"allowing you to create your menus without having to manually edit the \n"
"<path>menu.xml</path> file. It is a very small application and offers a \n"
"nice amount of customisation without typing any XML.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:243
#, no-wrap
msgid "Openbox theme and behaviour configuration"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:247
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Aside from being minimalistic and lightweight, Openbox is also surprisingly\n"
"customisable and flexible. As a user, you can easily change various settings\n"
"related to theme, appearance, window placement, docking, and more. There are two\n"
"options for configuring these settings within Openbox. You may either manually\n"
"edit <path>~/.config/openbox/rc.xml</path>, or you may want a GUI to help you\n"
"quickly change settings.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:256
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you want to manually edit <path>rc.xml</path>, you simply open up your\n"
"favourite text editor and start making changes. You might want to make a backup\n"
"of the original file just in case, and store it in a location like\n"
"<path>~/.config/openbox/rc.xml.default</path>. There are plenty of comments\n"
"within the document itself that should help you with editing. Alternatively, you\n"
"may want to look at the <uri\n"
"link=\"http://icculus.org/openbox/index.php/Help:Contents#Configuration\">Openbox\n"
"configuration guides</uri>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:267
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If manually editing <path>rc.xml</path> doesn't sound like your cup of tea, you\n"
"may want to use the GTK+ application to manage your themes and behaviours in\n"
"Openbox. The application that you will use is called ObConf, and can be\n"
"installed on your system just as easily as was Openbox itself.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:273
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing ObConf"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:274
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>emerge obconf</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:278
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You can then open the configurator by typing <c>obconf</c> in your terminal.\n"
"Next, you can go and add an entry for ObConf into your <path>menu.xml</path> so\n"
"it will show up in your Openbox menu.  If the \"editing the menu.xml file\" code \n"
"listing above seemed too vague to be helpful, we'll use ObConf as an example of \n"
"a menu entry:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:286
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"&lt;?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?&gt;\n"
"&lt;openbox_menu&gt;\n"
"&lt;menu id=\"1\" label=\"Configuration\"&gt;\n"
"  &lt;item label=\"OpenBox Config\"&gt;\n"
"    &lt;action name=\"execute\"&gt;&lt;execute&gt;/usr/bin/obconf&lt;/execute&gt;&lt;/action&gt;\n"
"  &lt;/item&gt;\n"
"&lt;/menu&gt;\n"
"&lt;/openbox_menu&gt;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:297
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"While ObConf is a great GUI tool for editing many behaviour-related settings \n"
"for Openbox, it doesn't allow one to manipulate nearly as many settings as \n"
"are presented in the <path>rc.xml</path> file itself.  If you are having \n"
"trouble finding a particular setting which you would like to change, please \n"
"consult the <uri link=\"http://openbox.org/wiki/Configuration\">Openbox Wiki</uri> \n"
"for more information.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><note>
#: en/openbox.xml:306
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In recent versions of Openbox (namely >3.4.7.2), one may experience a delay \n"
"in the submenu opening.  This setting was introduced into the rc.xml file, and \n"
"is listed as &lt;submenuShowDelay&gt;100&lt;/submenuShowDelay&gt;.  Simply \n"
"choose a lower number that suits your needs.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:315
#, no-wrap
msgid "Autostart configuration"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:319
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"As mentioned above, you don't see a whole lot when you issue the <c>startx</c>\n"
"command for the first time after installing Openbox. In addition to customising\n"
"your menus and changing the behaviour of the window manager, you will probably\n"
"want to have some programs automatically start with your Openbox session. There\n"
"is an easily-editable <path>autostart.sh</path> script that allows you to do\n"
"just that. Just like with the <path>menu.xml</path> file, there are two\n"
"different locations of the <path>autostart.sh</path> script--the system-wide\n"
"(<path>/etc/xdg/openbox/autostart.sh</path>), and the user-defined\n"
"(<path>~/.config/openbox/autostart.sh</path>).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:331
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In the default <path>autostart.sh</path>, you will notice a bunch of lines\n"
"calling for programs like the gnome-settings-daemon, XDG, and others. These\n"
"lines will generate errors upon logout if you don't have the programs installed\n"
"and configured. The easiest thing to do when getting started with Openbox is to\n"
"just comment out these lines by using the # symbol."
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:337
#, no-wrap
msgid "Commenting out lines in autostart.sh"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:338
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# Run XDG autostart things. By default don't run anything desktop-specific\n"
"# DESKTOP_ENV=\"\"\n"
"# if which /usr/lib/openbox/xdg-autostart >/dev/null; then\n"
"#  /usr/lib/openbox/xdg-autostart $DESKTOP_ENV\n"
"# fi\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:346
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In the above example, the comment symbol (#) was added before each line. The\n"
"commenting method is preferred to just deleting the lines because you may want\n"
"to add support for some of those startup items at a later time. Thus, leaving\n"
"the default lines in place could ease that process.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:353
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Adding your own programs to the <path>autostart.sh</path> script is as easy as\n"
"writing in the program name for many applications. For instance, if you have\n"
"<uri link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/app-admin/conky\">Conky</uri> (a\n"
"lightweight system monitor) installed, and want it to start automatically with\n"
"your Openbox session, you simply add the following line to your\n"
"<path>autostart.sh</path>:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:361
#, no-wrap
msgid "Adding Conky to your autostart.sh"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:362
#, no-wrap
msgid "conky &amp;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:366
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The ampersand (&amp;) after the command allows that application to load up in\n"
"the background. You will most likely want to load all the applications in your\n"
"<path>autostart.sh</path> script in the background because doing so will let\n"
"Openbox and other programs load without the previous one finishing.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:375
#, no-wrap
msgid "Configuring PolKit"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:379
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Many applications depend on the <uri\n"
"link=\"http://hal.freedesktop.org/docs/PolicyKit\">PolKit</uri> authentication\n"
"framework. You may need a PolKit agent, such as <c>polkit-gnome</c>, running\n"
"in your Openbox session.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:386
#, no-wrap
msgid "First, install the agent:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:389
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing PolKit"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:390
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>emerge polkit-gnome</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:394
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now configure PolKit to start automatically when you login to Openbox. Add\n"
"the following line to <path>~/.config/openbox/autostart</path> (for a single\n"
"user) or <path>/etc/xdg/openbox/autostart.sh</path> (for all users):\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:399
#, no-wrap
msgid "Start PolKit automatically"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:400
#, no-wrap
msgid "sleep 1 &amp;&amp; /usr/libexec/polkit-gnome-authentication-agent-1 &amp;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:406
#, no-wrap
msgid "Setting the background"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:410
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Some things that you might take for granted in bigger desktop environments are\n"
"not included by default in Openbox. One such thing is setting your desktop\n"
"background. In order to place an image as your wallpaper, you will need to\n"
"emerge a program like <uri\n"
"link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/media-gfx/feh\">feh</uri> or <uri\n"
"link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/x11-misc/nitrogen\">nitrogen</uri>.\n"
"<c>feh</c> is a simple image viewer that can also set the background, <e>and</e>\n"
"it can easily be put into the autostart script. Once you have emerged\n"
"<c>feh</c>, you can issue the following command to set the background:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:421 en/openbox.xml:437
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using feh to set the background image"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:422
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<comment>(feh has many other options instead of --bg-scale, \n"
"which will scale the image to the screen dimensions.\n"
"Consult the feh documentation.)</comment>\n"
"$ <i>feh --bg-scale /path/to/image.jpg</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:429
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Once you have set the background manually, a file called <path>.fehbg</path>\n"
"will be created in your home directory. This file simply contains the above\n"
"command that you just entered in the terminal, and is automatically updated\n"
"when you issue a different background command. Now, to set your background\n"
"automatically upon login, you can add the following line to your\n"
"<path>autostart.sh</path> script:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:438
#, no-wrap
msgid "source $HOME/.fehbg &amp;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:442
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you don't particularly care for the idea of having to issue a command in the\n"
"terminal in order to set your background, you can alternatively use\n"
"<c>nitrogen</c>. It will allow you to set a folder for your background images,\n"
"view thumbnails of those images, and fit, stretch, or tile them to your\n"
"desktop.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:450
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Installing <c>nitrogen</c> and getting it into your Openbox menu requires a few\n"
"more steps than are readily apparent. First, you need to <c>emerge nitrogen</c>.\n"
"Second, you need to run <c>nitrogen</c> with your backgrounds folder appended:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:455
#, no-wrap
msgid "Starting nitrogen with your image folder"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:456
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>nitrogen /path/to/your/backgrounds/folder</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:460
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Third, you can set your background image, but it will not be there after you\n"
"logout. Just as with <c>feh</c>, you need to restore your background by editing\n"
"your <path>autostart.sh</path> script to have the following line:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:465
#, no-wrap
msgid "Restoring your background with nitrogen"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:466
#, no-wrap
msgid "nitrogen --restore &amp;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:470
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This will cause nitrogen to load automatically when you start your Openbox\n"
"session, and that can lead to a slightly slower load time than using feh.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:479
#, no-wrap
msgid "Programs to use with Openbox"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:484
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The following is a list of some programs which you might want to use within your\n"
"Openbox environment. While the list contains numerous terminal emulators, file\n"
"managers, panels, and more, it should by no means be considered exhaustive. If\n"
"none of the programs listed fit your needs, please check the appropriate\n"
"categories in Portage for more options.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:494
#, no-wrap
msgid "Terminal emulators"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:499
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri\n"
"    link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/lxde-base/lxterminal\">LXterminal</uri>\n"
"    is the default terminal emulator for LXDE. It is very lightweight, and based\n"
"    on VTE. While EvilVTE offers many more customisation options (including\n"
"    transparency), LXterminal has a graphical interface for some of the more\n"
"    common options (font, colors, et cetera).\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:507
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri\n"
"    link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/x11-terms/evilvte\">EvilVTE</uri> is\n"
"    an extremely lightweight terminal emulator based on (you guessed it) VTE. It\n"
"    supports tabs, multiple encodings, as well as an easy and extensible\n"
"    configuration file.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:514
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/x11-terms/mrxvt\">Mrxvt</uri>\n"
"    is a multi-tabbed rxvt clone with XFT, transparent background and CJK\n"
"    support. It also features session support for each tab.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:519
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/x11-terms/aterm\">Aterm</uri>\n"
"    supports transparency and backwards compatibility with rxvt. It was\n"
"    originally designed for the AfterStep window manager, but easily integrates\n"
"    with other environments.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:525
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/x11-terms/eterm\">Eterm</uri>\n"
"    is a terminal based on vt102 and designed to be a more feature-rich\n"
"    replacement for xterm.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:530
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri\n"
"    link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/x11-terms/rxvt-unicode\">Rxvt-unicode</uri>\n"
"    is a clone of rxvt that supports Unicode, daemons, embedded perl, and\n"
"    multiple fonts simultaneously.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:536
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri\n"
"    link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/x11-terms/terminal\">Terminal</uri>\n"
"    is the VTE-based default for the Xfce desktop environment, so it does\n"
"    require some Xfce libraries to run. However, it is still fairly speedy, and\n"
"    supports transparency and is easily customised.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:547
#, no-wrap
msgid "File managers"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:552
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri\n"
"    link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/x11-misc/pcmanfm\">PCManFM</uri> is\n"
"    the lightweight filemanager from LXDE. It supports tabbed browsing, drag and\n"
"    drop, thumbnails for images, bookmarks, volume management, searching, and\n"
"    more. It also provides supports for managing the desktop background and\n"
"    drawing desktop icons (both optionally).\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:560
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/xfce-base/thunar\">Thunar</uri>\n"
"    is the standard file manager from Xfce. It features a bulk renamer,\n"
"    user-customisable actions, and an extension framework, along with many\n"
"    optional plugins, such as media tag editing. It depends on several Xfce\n"
"    libraries, but it's still slimmed down compared to other file managers like\n"
"    Nautilus (from GNOME), and Konqueror (from KDE).\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:568
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri\n"
"    link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/gnome-base/nautilus\">Nautilus</uri>\n"
"    is the powerful file manager from the GNOME desktop environment. It features\n"
"    volume management, thumbnails for images, searching, and some system\n"
"    configuration. As it depends on many of the GNOME libraries for proper\n"
"    function, it can seem a bit heavy compared to some of the other file\n"
"    managers.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:577
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/app-misc/gentoo\">Gentoo</uri>\n"
"    (no relation to this glorious Linux distribution) is a two-pane style file\n"
"    manager. It is incredibly lightweight, but lacks a some features now\n"
"    prominent in modern file managers. It should definitely be considered for\n"
"    older hardware, or if you are wanting a barebones setup.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:584
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri\n"
"    link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/app-misc/emelfm2\">emelFM2</uri> is\n"
"    another file manager in the vein of Midnight Commander. It features a\n"
"    two-pane window. As with the Gentoo file manager (listed above), it is\n"
"    barebones and does not include many features prevalent in newer file\n"
"    managers. However, it also offers a few features not found in other file\n"
"    managers, such as a built-in commandline in a separate pane.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:597
#, no-wrap
msgid "Desktop management"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:602
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    Though <uri\n"
"    link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/x11-misc/pcmanfm\">PCManFM</uri> is\n"
"    mainly a file manager, it also gives you the option to manage the desktop\n"
"    background (instead of using <c>feh</c> or <c>nitrogen</c>) and draw\n"
"    desktop icons.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:609
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/x11-misc/idesk\">iDesk</uri> is\n"
"    a simple program used to draw desktop icons. It supports shadowed and\n"
"    anti-aliased fonts, PNG images, \"snap-to-grid\" placement, and changing the\n"
"    desktop background.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:619
#, no-wrap
msgid "Panels"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:624
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri link=\"http://code.google.com/p/tint2/\">Tint2</uri> is a simple,\n"
"    lightweight panel and taskbar. It supports color, transparency, a clock,\n"
"    drag and drop between virtual desktops, a system tray, and comes with a\n"
"    battery monitor. You can even add a button to display the applications menu\n"
"    from your window manager.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:631
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri\n"
"    link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/x11-misc/pypanel\">PyPanel</uri> is\n"
"    an easily customised panel written in Python and C. It features\n"
"    transparency, shading, tinting, location and layout configuration, font\n"
"    type, autohiding, application launcher, clock, and more.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:638
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri\n"
"    link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/lxde-base/lxpanel\">LXPanel</uri> is\n"
"    the default panel and taskbar from LXDE. It features a launcher, menu,\n"
"    clock, and a GUI-based configurator. It is feature-rich while depending on\n"
"    very few packages, making it a good choice for a lean system.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:645
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri\n"
"    link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/xfce-base/xfce4-panel\">Xfce4-panel</uri>\n"
"    is the default panel from the Xfce desktop environment. It supports\n"
"    application launchers, detachable menus, a pager, tasklist, clock, applets,\n"
"    and more.  It does, however, require a few of the Xfce libraries which are\n"
"    not dependencies of some other panels.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:653
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri\n"
"    link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/x11-misc/fbpanel\">FBpanel</uri> is\n"
"    a simple, extremely lightweight panel that supports window lists, launchers,\n"
"    a clock, and a few other goodies. It's not the most featureful panel, and it\n"
"    can be cumbersome to configure, but it needs only GTK+ to run.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:664
#, no-wrap
msgid "Pagers and systrays"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:669
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri\n"
"    link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/x11-misc/netwmpager\">NetWMpager</uri>\n"
"    is an EWMH-compliant pager that integrates nicely into any of the *box\n"
"    environments. It is not as obtrusive, and is much more readily customisable\n"
"    than many of the other available pagers.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:676
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri\n"
"    link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/x11-misc/bbpager\">BBpager</uri> is\n"
"    a desktop pager that was originally written for BlackBox, but works nicely\n"
"    with Openbox as well. It does have some BlackBox dependencies though.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:682
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri\n"
"    link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/x11-plugins/docker\">Docker</uri> is\n"
"    the system tray that is made especially for Openbox. It has no extra\n"
"    dependencies, and gives you the ability to view and use tray icons for\n"
"    supported GTK and QT-based applications.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:689
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/x11-misc/trayer\">Trayer</uri>\n"
"    is a system tray that was modified from the FBpanel code, and is often used\n"
"    with FVWM. One of its perks is that it supports transparency.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:698
#, no-wrap
msgid "Session management"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:703
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/lxde-base/lxsession\">\n"
"    LXsession</uri> is the stripped down session manager from LXDE. It is\n"
"    designed to remember applications that the user was running at the last\n"
"    logout, and to automatically restart those programs. It also supports the\n"
"    HAL daemon.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:710
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/xfce-base/xfce4-session\">\n"
"    Xfce4-session</uri> is the session manager from, you guessed it, Xfce.  It\n"
"    is capable of saving several sessions, and provides methods for logging out,\n"
"    rebooting, and suspending your computer.  It does, however, have many Xfce\n"
"    dependencies.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:721
#, no-wrap
msgid "Configuration tools"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:726
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/x11-misc/obconf\">ObConf</uri>\n"
"    is a GUI application allowing you to customise the Openbox window manager\n"
"    without manually editing <path>~/.config/openbox/rc.conf</path>.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:731
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri\n"
"    link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/lxde-base/lxappearance\">LXappearance</uri>\n"
"    is a GTK theme and icon configurator used with LXDE.  It provides a nice\n"
"    graphical interface for setting the theme and icons, while depending on very\n"
"    few extra libraries.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:738
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri\n"
"    link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/x11-themes/gtk-chtheme\">GTK-ChTheme</uri>\n"
"    is a simple application allowing for easier switching of GTK themes and your\n"
"    font. Currently, it does not allow for the switching of icon themes.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:744
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri\n"
"    link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/x11-themes/gtk-theme-switch\">GTK-theme-switch</uri>\n"
"    is another simple application that lets you change your GTK theme.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:753
#, no-wrap
msgid "Miscellaneous"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:758
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/app-admin/conky\">Conky</uri>\n"
"    is a lightweight system monitor that can display over 250 objects, including\n"
"    date and time, CPU usage, memory usage, IMAP/POP3 email, top processes,\n"
"    hardware sensor data, and even info from your music player. It is highly\n"
"    customisable both in appearance and data display. We also have a <uri\n"
"    link=\"/doc/en/conky-howto.xml\">Conky configuration guide</uri> available.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:766
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri\n"
"    link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/app-editors/leafpad\">Leafpad</uri>\n"
"    is a simple text editor. It is very lightweight, but includes features like\n"
"    codeset options, and the ability to undo/redo without limits.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:772
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/media-gfx/feh\">feh</uri> is a\n"
"    simple image viewer that runs from the terminal, but it also has many other\n"
"    features. It can display a slideshow of images, create an index print,\n"
"    dynamically zoom, and set the desktop background (detailed instructions\n"
"    above).\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:779
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri\n"
"    link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/media-gfx/gpicview\">GPicView</uri>\n"
"    is a GUI-based image viewer. Though it has more dependencies than\n"
"    <c>feh</c>, it is incredibly quick to load and run.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:785
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri link=\"http://packages.gentoo.org/package/x11-misc/slim\">SLiM</uri> is\n"
"    the Simple Login Manager, which allows you to login to your Openbox session\n"
"    via a graphical interface instead of the terminal. It has very few\n"
"    dependencies, and supports many themes, but should not be used on machines\n"
"    that require remote logins.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:798
#, no-wrap
msgid "Openbox inside desktop environments"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:800
#, no-wrap
msgid "LXDE"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:804
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If installing each component of a working environment sounds like a little\n"
"<e>too</e> much customisation, but you still want the flexibility of Openbox,\n"
"you may want to look into a desktop environment that uses Openbox as its default\n"
"window manager. That environment is <uri link=\"http://www.lxde.org/\">LXDE</uri>,\n"
"the Lightweight X Desktop Environment. Designed to require even fewer system\n"
"resources than Xfce, it is built around Openbox.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:815
#, no-wrap
msgid "Openbox inside GNOME"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:819
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you already have a GNOME environment installed, you may just want to replace\n"
"the Metacity window manager with Openbox. Fortunately, this is quite a simple\n"
"task! You will need to fire up your favourite editor, open your\n"
"<path>~/.xinitrc</path> file, and put the following command inside it:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:825
#, no-wrap
msgid "Adding an Openbox-GNOME session to your .xinitrc"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:826
#, no-wrap
msgid "exec openbox-gnome-session\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:830
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you use GDM or another graphical login manager, you will see a new\n"
"\"GNOME/Openbox\" option in your session menu. You can simply select that option\n"
"instead of manually editing your <path>~/.xinitrc</path>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:838
#, no-wrap
msgid "Openbox inside KDE"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:842
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Say you have KDE installed and like it, but you want more flexibility with your\n"
"window management than KWin offers. You can use Openbox as your window manager\n"
"inside of KDE by simply editing your <path>~/.xinitrc</path> file, and\n"
"replacing your current exec command with the following:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:848
#, no-wrap
msgid "Adding an Openbox-KDE session to your .xinitrc"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:849
#, no-wrap
msgid "exec openbox-kde-session\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:853
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now when you issue <c>startx</c> you will see KDE, but instead of KWin, you\n"
"will have the customisability of the Openbox window manager.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:858
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you use KDM or another graphic login manager, you will see a new\n"
"\"KDE/Openbox\" option in your session menu. You can simply select that option\n"
"instead of manually editing your <path>~/.xinitrc</path>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><note>
#: en/openbox.xml:864
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This method of using Openbox with KDE has been tested with the KDE 3.x\n"
"releases. While it seems highly likely that it will work with the KDE 4.x\n"
"series, it has not been thoroughly tested as of yet.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:872
#, no-wrap
msgid "Openbox inside Xfce"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:876
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you use Xfce4 and would like to replace xfwm4 with Openbox, you will need to\n"
"go about it a little differently than with KDE or GNOME. First, you need to\n"
"start your normal Xfce session, and open up a terminal. From the terminal,\n"
"issue the following command:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:882
#, no-wrap
msgid "Killing xfwm4 and replacing it with Openbox"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:883
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>killall xfwm4 ; openbox &amp; exit</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:887
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Second, you need to exit out of your Xfce session, and make sure to tick the\n"
"checkbox that says \"Save session for future login.\"  This will keep Openbox as\n"
"your default window manager. Third, you will notice that you can't logout\n"
"properly when using the default menu action. To fix this problem, open up your\n"
"<path>menu.xml</path>, and locate this line:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:894
#, no-wrap
msgid "Finding the exit action in menu.xml"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:895
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"&lt;item label=\"Exit\"&gt;\n"
"     &lt;action name=\"Exit\"/&gt;\n"
"&lt;/item&gt;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:901
#, no-wrap
msgid "Change it to this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:904
#, no-wrap
msgid "Replacing the exit action in menu.xml"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/openbox.xml:905
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"&lt;item label=\"Exit\"&gt;\n"
"  &lt;action name=\"Execute\"&gt;\n"
"    &lt;command&gt;xfce4-session-logout&lt;/command&gt;\n"
"  &lt;/action&gt;\n"
"&lt;/item&gt;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><note>
#: en/openbox.xml:913
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"With Xfce4, the root-menu provided by Xfdesktop will be used instead of the\n"
"Openbox root-menu.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:922
#, no-wrap
msgid "Further documentation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/openbox.xml:924
#, no-wrap
msgid "External resources"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/openbox.xml:928
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"While this document will easily take you through the inital installation and\n"
"customisation of Openbox, it is by no means the only reference on the topic.\n"
"There are several other resources that will aid you in creating your perfect\n"
"Openbox setup. Some of them are listed below:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:936
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    On <uri link=\"http://openbox.org/\">The Official Openbox website</uri> \n"
"    you will find more detailed information regarding theming, creating menus \n"
"    (including pipe menus), autostart scripting, and much more. This site also \n"
"    has information regarding new releases, upgrades, and instructions on how \n"
"    you can contribute to development.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:943
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    The <uri link=\"http://urukrama.wordpress.com/openbox-guide/\">Urukrama's\n"
"    Guide to Openbox</uri> blog contains a plethora of information about\n"
"    switching GTK+ themes, setting up keybindings, desktop effects, and other\n"
"    programs to use in conjunction with Openbox. Though the tutorial was\n"
"    originally written for use with Ubuntu, everything is applicable to Gentoo\n"
"    (and other Linux distributions for that matter).\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/openbox.xml:951
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri link=\"http://www.box-look.org/\">Box-Look</uri> provides numerous\n"
"    themes, icons, wallpapers, fonts, and tools to be used with Openbox (as well\n"
"    as the other *box window managers like Fluxbox, Blackbox, PekWM, etc.)\n"
"  "
msgstr ""
